        "comment": {
            "name": "comment",
            "type": "com.atlassian.jira.issue.fields.CommentSystemField",
            "value": [
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/46060",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=ckaufman",
                        "name": "ckaufman",
                        "displayName": "Cory Kaufman",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "I ran another test on this today and I was able to view the email addresses. I think maybe it was a server configuration issue. You can close this ticket.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=ckaufman",
                        "name": "ckaufman",
                        "displayName": "Cory Kaufman",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2011-04-27T07:00:35.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2011-04-27T07:00:35.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/46065",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=redthor",
                        "name": "redthor",
                        "displayName": "Douglas Reith",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "I'm experiencing this issue. My environment is:\r\nDebian Squeeze\r\nApache2.2\r\nPHP\/5.3.3-7+squeeze1\r\nCakePHP + Zend Framework\r\nZend_Mail\r\n\r\n{code}\r\n\/\/ $message instanceof Zend_Mail_Part\r\n$recipient = implode($message->getHeader('to', 'array'));\r\n\r\n\/\/ $recipient never contains the email address found in the less than '<', greater than '>' brackets.\r\n{code}\r\n\r\nFor example, if the header contains <doug@somedomain.com> then I get nothing. Or if it contains \"Doug R\"  <doug@somedomain.com> then I get \"Doug R\"\r\n\r\nCorey said it is a server config issue. Could you tell me what can be changed in the environment to fix this?\r\n\r\nThanks.\r\n",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=redthor",
                        "name": "redthor",
                        "displayName": "Douglas Reith",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2011-04-27T23:23:20.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2011-04-27T23:23:20.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/46066",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=ckaufman",
                        "name": "ckaufman",
                        "displayName": "Cory Kaufman",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Unfortunately I don't know-- I'm not in control of the server. It would be really nice to know what is causing this bug though, in case it happens again.\r\n",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=ckaufman",
                        "name": "ckaufman",
                        "displayName": "Cory Kaufman",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2011-04-28T00:30:01.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2011-04-28T00:30:01.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/46068",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=redthor",
                        "name": "redthor",
                        "displayName": "Douglas Reith",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Ok, think i've found it.\r\n\r\nTrick is that CakePHP developers have done their job and prevent somebody malicious entering in nefarious tags by cutting out anything with '<' and '>' in it. Basically anything that looks like a tag is removed. The headers are saved to the DB but stripped out when retrieved.\r\n\r\nDefinitely not a Zend_Mail bug.\r\n\r\nIf anyone wanders into this that's using CakePHP, the relevant section is highlighted in yellow at the top of this page:\r\nhttp:\/\/book.cakephp.org\/view\/1183\/Data-Sanitization",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=redthor",
                        "name": "redthor",
                        "displayName": "Douglas Reith",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2011-04-28T06:30:01.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2011-04-28T06:30:01.000+0000"
                }
            ]
        }
    },
